      "id": 358177,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>In glycerol metabolism, the oxidation of <i>sn</i>-glycerol 3-phosphate to give dihydroxyacetone phosphate is catalyzed by <i>sn</i>-glycerol-3-phosphate dehydrogenase, with NAD<sup>+</sup> as cofactor. The reaction is stereospecific, occurring exclusively on the Re face of the nicotinamide ring.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBdXdaIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--1ab79c883d6eaacf7eed90241dc5395c48a1cf23/OChem_29_EC_017.jpg\" alt=\"A reaction with nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide cation oxidizes sn-glycerol-3-phosphate to dihydroxyactone phosphate. Nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide cation converts to nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide hydride\">\n<p>Which hydrogen in the NADH product comes from <i>sn</i>-glycerol 3-phosphate? Does it have pro-<i>R</i> or pro-<i>S</i> stereochemistry?</p>",
